<Folder><name>Drive-up Boondocking</name>
<Placemark>
  <name>Search Bay</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Official site page<br/><b>Confidence:</b> High<br/><b>Fee:</b> Not listed on official page<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Not stated<br/><b>Water:</b> No potable water<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No restrooms<br/><b>Access:</b> Single-track dirt road (FR 3436) from M-134 to unimproved bay-edge camping area.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> 2WD possible in dry conditions; scout if wet.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Primitive camping with no tables, toilets, or drinking water. Good honest example of a real official dispersed-style pin.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.fs.usda.gov/r09/hiawatha/recreation/search-bay<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.fs.usda.gov/r09/hiawatha/recreation/camping-cabins?page=%2C5]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.516421,45.994052,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Hickey Marsh Dispersed Camping</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> $0 reported<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Just off M-28 on an unmarked side road about 1/4–1/2 mile in.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Short dirt-road access; scout ahead before committing larger rigs.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Free dispersed area with established parking spots and campfire remnants; no official signage.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.campendium.com/hickey-marsh-dispersed-camping<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.campgroundviews.com/listing/hickey-marsh-dispersed-camping/]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.5037,46.3546,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>USFS 3536 Dispersed Site</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / typically free dispersed use<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Forest Service road access; reviewers describe easy access from M-28.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Drive-in dispersed stop; verify surface and any seasonal closures before heading in.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Appears to function as a simple dispersed pull-in/lot style stop rather than a developed campground.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/usfs-3536<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/newberry/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.82903811659388,46.35276778604294,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Adams Trail Dirt Lot</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Large flat dirt lot used as a snowmobile lot in winter and dispersed camping area otherwise.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Reported suitable for motorhomes up to about 26 ft.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Useful near Pictured Rocks when you want a simple overnight base rather than a scenic lakeshore site.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/adams-trail-dirt-lot<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/pictured-rocks-national-park/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.22152352,46.52726419,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Lake Superior North Shore</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Lakefront dispersed area; reports mention sand and seasonal surface changes.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> 4WD recommended for sandier sections.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Waterfront dispersed option with more adventure factor and more risk of getting sloppy in wet or sandy conditions. Check local signage and current conditions before assuming shoreline camping is still allowed in every pull-off nearby.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/lake-superior-north-shore<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-85.02278517,46.76308903,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Peninsula Point Lighthouse Access Road - Dispersed</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported at camping pull-offs<br/><b>Toilet:</b> Pit toilets at lighthouse area<br/><b>Access:</b> Established dispersed sites along the access road, mostly about a mile before the lighthouse.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Narrow one-lane road with pullouts; smaller rigs easier. Camp only in clearly established areas.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Nice shoreline option, but it is not a place to bully a giant RV down a narrow road and expect serenity.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/peninsula-point-lighthouse-access-road-hiawatha-forest<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/trenary/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.96643218,45.68067414,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Mouth of the Huron Dispersed Camping</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> First come, first served<br/><b>Water:</b> No potable water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> Porta potties reported by users<br/><b>Access:</b> Well-maintained gravel road to beach camping area; passenger cars usually okay, 4WD helpful deeper in.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Best for smaller/self-contained setups if you want flexibility on sand.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Direct beach camping on Lake Superior. Big views, limited services, and that classic 'you came here for wilderness, not hookups' energy.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/mouth-of-the-huron-dispersed-camping<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/marquette/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-88.04411436,46.91048331,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Lake Perrault</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin with local corroboration<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Free per travel guide source<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No potable water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Road off M-26 down to lakeside dirt area and campsites.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Tight turnaround; avoid taking anything over about 40 ft.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Cleared areas with fire rings and a few picnic tables; easy lake access and a trail around the lake.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/lake-perrault<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.takethetruck.com/blog/free-camping-michigan-up]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-88.73128049,47.02924716,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Hovey Lake Campsites</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Official site page<br/><b>Confidence:</b> High<br/><b>Fee:</b> $0 official no-fee area<br/><b>Reservation:</b> First come, first served<br/><b>Water:</b> Official page says potable water not available<br/><b>Toilet:</b> Official page says restrooms not available<br/><b>Access:</b> Forest-road approach via FR 2254 to FR 2473 and FR 2367 south of M-94.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Forest-road access is fine for normal self-contained rigs in decent conditions; still not a place to arrive cocky after heavy rain.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Official Hiawatha page lists four quiet lake-edge campsites with tables and fire rings. Nice fit for the boondocking layer because it is no-fee and low-service, even though it is an established site cluster.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.fs.usda.gov/r09/hiawatha/recreation/hovey-lake-campsites<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.takethetruck.com/blog/free-camping-michigan-up]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.7006,46.2905,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Mackinac Trail Camp</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> $0 reported<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Drive-in dispersed spot on Mackinac Trail corridor north of St. Ignace.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Simple self-contained stop; check sand and turnaround before driving bigger rigs in at dusk like a hero.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Exact Dyrt listing for Mackinac Trail Camp. Nearby dispersed reviews make this a useful Straits-area overnight lead, but it still behaves like a primitive pull-in rather than a developed campground.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/mackinac-trail-camp<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/mackinaw-city/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.71970345,46.01860055,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Wide Waters Dispersed Camping</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Gravel approach to a broad sandy/open staging-style area near the Paradise / Whitefish Point corridor.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Easy in and out for many rigs, but loose sand can still embarrass the overconfident.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Dyrt reviews describe a wide sandy meadow/open pull-around area with established fire rings, bigger-rig room, daytime ATV/truck traffic, and heavy bugs at times. Better described as a functional dispersed landing than a tucked-away forest hideout.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/wide-waters-dispersed-camping<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/paradise/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-85.12638008,46.6410352,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Rhody Trail Pull Off</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> $0 reported<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported at the site<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Turn south off H-58 onto Rhody Creek Trail and look for cleared areas about 0.75 to 1 mile in.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Maintained gravel approach; generally friendly for vans, trailers, and RVs that can tolerate a basic forest-road setup.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Practical free pull-off style dispersed area off H-58 / Rhody Creek corridor near Log Slide and Au Sable. Useful when you want free and functional rather than scenic perfection.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/rhody-trail-pull-off<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/grand-marais/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.09568057,46.62786468,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Moose Rapids Campground</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Official campground page + crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Donation recommended<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> Water pump reported by travel source<br/><b>Toilet:</b> Porta potties / rustic toilets reported<br/><b>Access:</b> County road access to a rustic township camping area on the Michigamme River near Republic.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Mix of smaller wooded sites and a couple roomier river-adjacent sites; better for self-contained campers than giant luxury barges.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Republic Township officially confirms Moose Rapids as a transient rustic campground with donation-based operation and stay rules; the exact map coordinate comes from Campendium. Useful low-cost primitive stop west of Marquette.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.republicmichigan.com/organizations/campgrounds/moose-rapids-campground/<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.campendium.com/moose-rapids-township]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-88.0766,46.4562,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Porcupine Mountains Boundary Dispersed Site</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Travel-guide exact pin with forest-rule support<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> $0 reported<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Smooth gravel approach off South Boundary Road at the Ottawa / Porkies edge.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Travel source reports larger RVs can manage this one; still scout mud and washboard because the UP likes surprising people.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Take The Truck describes established fire pits and some picnic tables near the Porcupine Mountains boundary. Ottawa officially allows dispersed camping in general forest areas subject to its stay and relocation rules.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.takethetruck.com/blog/free-camping-michigan-up<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.fs.usda.gov/r09/ottawa/alerts/occupancy-and-use-forest-order-09-07-21-04]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-89.76244,46.70982,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Castle Rock Ponds</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No potable water reported<br/><b>Toilet:</b> No toilet reported<br/><b>Access:</b> Decent gravel road into pond-side dispersed clearings west of St. Ignace.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Reported workable for standard vehicles and mid-size rigs; flatter and easier than some sandier shoreline spots.<br/><b>Notes:</b> The Dyrt places this as a bare-bones dispersed area with room for multiple rigs around the ponds. Good add because it fills the St. Ignace corridor with another usable exact pin that is not pretending to be a full campground.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/castle-rock-ponds<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/cross-village/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.7958525754365,45.92394461426288,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Coalwood Trail - Dispersed Campsite</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Drive-in dispersed site off Coalwood Trail in Hiawatha NF.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Standard vehicles usually fine in decent conditions; very buggy and limited services.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Dyrt lists this as a drive-in dispersed site with exact coordinates. Review notes a small pond nearby and serious mosquito pressure.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/dispersed-camping-off-coalwood-trail<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/wetmore/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.5648994,46.36429086,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Dispersed Camping Hovey Lake Equine Trailhead</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Trailhead-style access with drive-in parking plus walk-in/hike-in use options.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Fine for normal self-contained rigs in dry weather; this is primitive trailhead country, not luxury resort country.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Dyrt lists drive-in, walk-in, and hike-in dispersed access at the Hovey Lake equine trailhead with exact coordinates.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/dispersed-camping-hovey-lake-equine-trailhead<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://www.fs.usda.gov/r09/hiawatha/maps-guides]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.70274273218466,46.28728852524713,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Herman Lake Dispersed</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Primitive one-lane road about 1.5–2 miles in from the main access.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Deeply rutted/muddy access; not recommended for trailers or low-clearance vehicles.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Remote, private lake-adjacent dispersed spot. Dyrt review specifically warns about a deeply rutted muddy road and says towing in is a bad idea.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/herman-lake<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/wetmore/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-86.58649797,46.24077521,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Mackinac Trail Spur Site</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Crowdsourced exact pin<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed stop<br/><b>Reservation:</b> Permit may be required / check locally<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Drive-in spur off the Mackinac Trail corridor; review describes a sand road then a left turn into a grassy area.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> Smaller/self-contained rigs are the safer bet; sand can be rude to complacent drivers.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Popular Straits-area dispersed lead with a positive 2025 review describing flowers, monarch butterflies, and a grassy opening near the lighthouse/ferry corridor.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/mackinac-trail-spur-site<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/moran/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.71854443839761,46.03605104714077,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>Carp River Boat Launch</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Boat-launch exact point + camping reviews<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown / treated as dispersed overnight-use spot<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> None noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Gravel road to Lake Huron launch area; reviews mention deep potholes but generally manageable access.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> 2WD usually okay if you take the potholes seriously and do not drive like a stunt coordinator.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Exact launch point comes from Outdoor Michigan; overnight use comes from current Dyrt dispersed-camping reviews describing water views, privacy, and easy access to Lake Huron.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://outdoormichigan.org/feature/10420<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://thedyrt.com/camping/michigan/near/saint-ignace/with/dispersed]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-84.69105,46.02017,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
<Placemark>
  <name>High Rock Bay</name>
  <styleUrl>#Drive-up Boondocking</styleUrl>
  <description><![CDATA[<b>Category:</b> Boondocking / dispersed<br/><b>Status:</b> Named candidate in managed dispersed-recreation area<br/><b>Confidence:</b> Medium<br/><b>Fee:</b> Unknown<br/><b>Reservation:</b> None noted<br/><b>Water:</b> No potable water noted<br/><b>Toilet:</b> None noted<br/><b>Access:</b> Remote unpaved approach on High Rock Bay Road / Keweenaw Point roads to bay-end camping area.<br/><b>Vehicle Note:</b> 4WD strongly recommended; travel sources describe a rough, potentially swampy road.<br/><b>Notes:</b> Keweenaw Point state-managed lands are managed primarily for dispersed recreation such as camping. Secondary travel source gives exact bay coordinates and explicitly describes overlanders and campers using the area.<br/><b>Primary Source URL:</b> https://www.michigan.gov/dnr/managing-resources/prd/parks/mgt-plans/keweenaw-point-state-lands<br/><b>Secondary Source URL:</b> https://freshcoastcabins.com/activities/high-rock-bay/]]></description>
  <Point><coordinates>-87.428832,47.255828,0</coordinates></Point>
</Placemark>
</Folder><Folder><name>Official Primitive Sites</name>
